04716nam a22006855i 9780520917125DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19931993cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209171257 a10.1525/97805209171252doi  a(DE-B1597)648500  a(OCoLC)1414457458  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBM496.9.S48bB69 1995eb 7aREL0400002bisacsh04a296.1/22201 aBoyarin, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCarnal Israel :bReading Sex in Talmudic Culture /cDaniel Boyarin; ed. by Daniel Boyarin. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1993] 4c©1993  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe New Historicism: Studies in Cultural Poetics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on the Term Rabbis -- tIntroduction -- t1 "Behold Israel According to the Flesh" On Anthropology and Sexuality in Late-Antique Judaisms -- t2 Dialectics of Desire "The Evil Instinct Is Very Good" -- t3 Different Eves: Myths of Female Origins and the Discourse of Married Sex -- t4 Engendering Desire: Husbands, Wives, and Sexual Intercourse -- t5 Lusting After Learning The Torah as "the Other Woman" -- t6 Studying Women: Resistance from Within the Male Discourse -- t7 (Re)producing Men: Constructing the Rabbinic Male Body -- tConcluding Forward: Talmudic Study as Cultural Critique -- tBibliography -- tGeneral Index -- tIndex of Primary Jewish Texts0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBeginning with a startling endorsement of the patristic view of Judaism—that it was a "carnal" religion, in contrast to the spiritual vision of the Church—Daniel Boyarin argues that rabbinic Judaism was based on a set of assumptions about the human body that were profoundly different from those of Christianity. The body—specifically, the sexualized body—could not be renounced, for the Rabbis believed as a religious principle in the generation of offspring and hence in intercourse sanctioned by marriage.This belief bound men and women together and made impossible the various modes of gender separation practiced by early Christians. The commitment to coupling did not imply a resolution of the unequal distribution of power that characterized relations between the sexes in all late-antique societies. But Boyarin argues strenuously that the male construction and treatment of women in rabbinic Judaism did not rest on a loathing of the female body. Thus, without ignoring the currents of sexual domination that course through the Talmudic texts, Boyarin insists that the rabbinic account of human sexuality, different from that of the Hellenistic Judaisms and Pauline Christianity, has something important and empowering to teach us today.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHuman body in rabbinical literature. 0aHuman bodyxReligious aspectsxJudaism. 0aJudaismxHistoryxTalmudic period, 10-425. 0aJudaismxHistoryyTalmudic period, 10-425. 0aRabbinical literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aSex in rabbinical literature. 0aSexxReligious aspectsxJudaism. 0aWomen in Judaism. 0aWomen in rabbinical literature. 4aGeneral. 4aJudaism. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh1 aBoyarin, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020336540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091712540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520917125423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520917125/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b200